## Set up PocketBase with Next.js

### 1. Download and run PocketBase
- Download the binary for your OS from https://pocketbase.io/docs:
  ```bash
  # Linux/Mac
  curl -LO https://github.com/pocketbase/pocketbase/releases/latest/download/pocketbase_linux_amd64.zip
  unzip pocketbase_linux_amd64.zip
  chmod +x pocketbase
  ./pocketbase serve
  ```
- PocketBase runs on `http://127.0.0.1:8090` by default.
- Admin UI: `http://127.0.0.1:8090/_/`
- Create your admin account on first visit.

### 2. Install the PocketBase JS SDK
```
npm install pocketbase
```

### 3. Create the PocketBase client (`lib/pocketbase.ts`)
```ts
import PocketBase from 'pocketbase';

const pb = new PocketBase(process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_POCKETBASE_URL);
export default pb;
```
- Add to `.env.local`:
  ```
  NEXT_PUBLIC_POCKETBASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:8090
  ```
- In production replace with your deployed PocketBase URL.
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_` is intentional here — the client SDK runs in the browser too.

### 4. Create collections in the Admin UI
- Go to `http://127.0.0.1:8090/_/` → Collections → New Collection.
- Example `posts` collection:
  - `title` (text, required)
  - `content` (editor)
  - `author` (relation → `users`)
  - `published` (bool)
- Set API Rules to control read/write access (e.g., `@request.auth.id != ''` for authenticated-only).

### 5. Fetch records (Server Component)
```ts
import PocketBase from 'pocketbase';

export default async function PostsPage() {
  // Use a server-side instance (not the shared client) to avoid cookie leaks
  const pb = new PocketBase(process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_POCKETBASE_URL);
  const posts = await pb.collection('posts').getFullList({
    sort: '-created',
    filter: 'published = true',
  });

  return (
    <ul>
      {posts.map(post => (
        <li key={post.id}>{post.title}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

### 6. Auth — sign up and sign in (Client Component)
```tsx
'use client';
import pb from '@/lib/pocketbase';

export function AuthForm() {
  async function handleSignIn(email: string, password: string) {
    try {
      await pb.collection('users').authWithPassword(email, password);
      // pb.authStore.token is now set and persisted in a cookie automatically
    } catch (e) {
      console.error('Auth failed', e);
    }
  }

  async function handleSignUp(email: string, password: string, name: string) {
    await pb.collection('users').create({ email, password, passwordConfirm: password, name });
    await pb.collection('users').authWithPassword(email, password);
  }

  function handleSignOut() {
    pb.authStore.clear();
  }

  // ...
}
```
- `pb.authStore` persists the token in a cookie (browser) or memory (Node.js).

### 7. Protect routes with middleware (`middleware.ts`)
```ts
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import type { NextRequest } from 'next/server';

export function middleware(request: NextRequest) {
  const authCookie = request.cookies.get('pb_auth');

  if (!authCookie && request.nextUrl.pathname.startsWith('/dashboard')) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL('/login', request.url));
  }

  return NextResponse.next();
}

export const config = {
  matcher: ['/dashboard/:path*'],
};
```
- PocketBase JS SDK stores auth in `pb_auth` cookie by default in browser environments.
- For full server-side session validation, load the PocketBase client from the cookie and call `pb.authStore.isValid`.

### 8. Real-time subscriptions (Client Component)
```tsx
'use client';
import pb from '@/lib/pocketbase';
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

export function LivePosts() {
  const [posts, setPosts] = useState<any[]>([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    pb.collection('posts').subscribe('*', ({ action, record }) => {
      if (action === 'create') setPosts(prev => [record, ...prev]);
      if (action === 'delete') setPosts(prev => prev.filter(p => p.id !== record.id));
    });
    return () => { pb.collection('posts').unsubscribe('*'); };
  }, []);

  return <ul>{posts.map(p => <li key={p.id}>{p.title}</li>)}</ul>;
}
```

### 9. File uploads
```ts
const formData = new FormData();
formData.append('avatar', fileInput.files[0]);
await pb.collection('users').update(pb.authStore.model!.id, formData);

// Get file URL
const avatarUrl = pb.files.getUrl(user, user.avatar, { thumb: '100x100' });
```

### 10. Deploy PocketBase to production
- **Railway / Render / Fly.io**: Upload the binary, expose port 8090, mount a persistent volume for `pb_data/`.
- **VPS**: Run as a systemd service. Reverse-proxy with Nginx.
- **Critical**: `pb_data/` directory contains your SQLite database. Mount it as a persistent volume — if it's ephemeral (like on Fly.io without a volume), you will lose all data on restart.
- Set `POCKETBASE_ADMIN_EMAIL` and `POCKETBASE_ADMIN_PASSWORD` as env vars for headless admin provisioning.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Failed to fetch` / CORS error** → Add your Next.js origin to PocketBase allowed origins: Admin UI → Settings → Application → Allowed Origins.
- **Auth token not persisting across page loads** → Use `pb.authStore.onChange` to sync to localStorage/cookie, or enable `pb.authStore.save()` explicitly.
- **Collection not found** → The collection name is case-sensitive and must match exactly.
- **File URL returns 404** → You're constructing the URL manually. Use `pb.files.getUrl(record, filename)` instead.
- **Real-time events stop after reconnect** → PocketBase SSE connections close after inactivity. The SDK auto-reconnects, but wrap subscriptions in a check for `pb.authStore.isValid`.
- **`pb_data` lost on redeploy** → You didn't mount a persistent volume. This is data loss — back up `pb_data/` before each deploy.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT use the shared `pb` client instance in Server Components or API routes — create a new `PocketBase` instance per request to avoid auth state leakage between users.
- Do NOT rely on client-side API rules bypass — always configure collection rules in the Admin UI. The JS SDK runs on the client and cannot be trusted.
- Do NOT store `pb_data/` in a non-persistent filesystem (container ephemeral disk). Always use a mounted volume.
- Do NOT expose the PocketBase admin credentials in environment variables accessible to the browser (`NEXT_PUBLIC_`).
- Do NOT use PocketBase's SQLite for high-write workloads (millions of writes/day). It is optimized for read-heavy workloads. Use Postgres-backed alternatives for high throughput.
- Do NOT skip configuring API Rules. By default, new collections are fully public — set authentication rules before going to production.
